\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
The Role of Gender in ICT-mediated Agricultural Information Campaigns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Bjorn Van Campenhout, Els Lecoutere, and David J Spielman
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
In programs to disseminate information through agricultural extension and
 advisory services, seemingly small design attributes—the way the information
 is delivered, who delivers the information, or who is targeted by the message—c
an result in significant differences in effectiveness and inclusiveness
 of the intervention.
 Information and communications technology (ICT) can reduce the costs associated
 with adapting design attributes to particular problems and contexts.
 This study investigates the impact of a video-mediated extension approach
 and the importance of the gender composition of the person(s) who provide(s)
 the information and the gender composition of the person(s) who receive(s)
 the information.
 We conduct a field experiment among smallholder maize farmers in Uganda
 to determine whether and how reductions in information asymmetries among
 and within households lead to a range of productivity- and welfare-improving
 outcomes.
 Specifically, we assess the effectiveness of the approach by measuring
 knowledge gained, adoption of modern inputs and recommend practices, maize
 production and disposal, and well-being.
 We assess the approach’s inclusivity by exploring gender-disaggregated
 effects on in intra-household decision-making, cooperative approaches to
 household farming, and other equity indicators.
 We find that short extension video messages increase knowledge, technology
 adoption, and production at the household level, especially when the informatio
n is targeted to both husband and wife as a couple.
 We also find that targeting the information to husband and wife jointly
 leads to a significant increase in joint decision-making.
 Most of these household level effects, however, work through male-managed
 and jointly-managed plots, and women seem less able to use the new information
 on plots they manage directly and independently.
 Furthermore, we find no evidence of homophily or role model effects resulting
 from short videos featuring farmer-actors who are similar to the farmers
 participating in the experiment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often, the poor appear to make sub-optimal decisions because they lack critical
 pieces of information, are unable to benefit from learning externalities
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1086/601447"

\end_inset

, fail to notice vital information 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1093/qje/qju015"

\end_inset

, or hold beliefs that are not true 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1162/qjec.2010.125.2.515,10.1257/app.3.1.1"

\end_inset

.
 In many instances, information campaigns, extension programs, or advisory
 services designed to address these information inefficiencies can lead
 to significant differences in an individual's decision-making 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "banerjee2011poor"

\end_inset

.
 In the context of smallholder agriculture, these inefficiencies have been
 well documented, especially where the lack of information about the existence,
 use, and profitability of modern inputs, improved technologies, and recommended
 management practices are a major constraint to sustainable crop intensification
, productivity growth, and food security 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1086/451461,jack2013market"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With new possibilities offered by information and communications technology
 (ICT), an abundance of pilot projects and commercial products have entered
 the market with a focus on revitalizing agricultural extension and advisory
 services in developing countries.
 However, a growing body of evidence suggests that not all ICT-mediated
 extension approaches are equally effective in achieving outcomes such as
 increased rates of technology adoption, higher crop yields, or improvements
 in household welfare and intra-household equity.
 Seemingly small design attributes—the way information is delivered, who
 delivers the information, and who was targeted—can significantly influence
 these outcomes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper investigates the effectiveness of information about improved
 maize cultivation delivered to smallholder farmers in Uganda.
 In a first part, we consider the technology through which the information
 is delivered to the farmer, and differentiate between (i) short audiovisual
 messages viewed on tablet computers; (ii) Interactive Voice Response (IVR)
 systems that can be called upon if the need arises; and (iii) short message
 service (sms) nudges that remind farmers at particular points in time about
 key farming practices.
 The outcomes used to judge the relative effectiveness of the the difference
 technologies are generally aggregated to the household level and include
 knowledge gained, practices and and modern inputs adopted, farm production
 and disposal, and household well-being.
 In a second part, the paper further explores the role and importance of
 gender-related attributes in the design of the video-mediated approach
 that influence the inclusivity of extension information delivery.
 In particular, we focus on (i) the gender composition of the receiver(s)
 of extension messages and (ii) the gender composition of the messenger(s)
 of the information message.
 Experimental variations in these attributes allows us to test hypotheses
 related to information asymmetries within (dual) households.
 In addition, it allows us to test hypotheses related to the efficacy of
 videos containing illustrative and expositional content to change certain
 customs, beliefs or gender stereotypes related to maize farming 
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A dual household is defined as a household containing both one male and
 one female member who take decisions as head of household either jointly
 or singly in their respective spheres of responsibility.
 It thus excludes single headed households or polygamous households.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The role of these gender related attributes is judged by looking at knowledge
 at the individual level, decision making within the households, as well
 as adoption and production outcomes conditional on who is the primary plot
 manager.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These hypotheses are tested using a field experiment in which farmers are
 randomly assigned to a group that receives a particular information interventio
n, and their outcomes are compared to the outcomes of a group of farmers
 that did not receive the information intervention 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "de2016field"

\end_inset

.
 As we want to test more than one research hypothesis and are particularly
 interested in comparing the relative effectiveness of various attributes
 of an ICT-mediated extension approach, we opt for a factorial design.
 Generally, in factorial designs, a smaller sample size is needed to answer
 a fixed number of research questions as opposed to parallel designs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We work with 3,600 participants sampled from the population of dual households
 cultivating maize across five districts of eastern Uganda.
 The core information interventions take the form of short videos that explain
 simple yet effective ways to increase maize productivity and profitability,
 such as best practices in row spacing, the importance of quality seed,
 optimal soil fertility management, and farm budget management.
 To test overall effectiveness of the information provided through the video,
 we compare outcomes of farmers that were exposed to a placebo video to
 outcomes of farmers that were shown the video.
 To about two third of the sample of farm households that were shown the
 agricultural information video, we also gave to toll free phone number
 and explained they could call this number any time if they needed more
 information on maize farming.
 Finally, to half of the sample of households that got the IVR number (and
 thus were also shown the video) we sent 10 sms messages at strategic points
 in time reminding them to about the importance of a particular technology
 or practice that was explained in the video and repeating that they can
 always call the IVR system if they want more information.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To test how information asymmetry within the household affects decision
 making and outcomes, we compare farm households where the video was shown
 only to the man in the household (the status quo) to households where the
 video was shown to the woman in the household, and to households where
 the video was shown to man and women together as a couple.
 To test the hypothesis on the importance of the gender (composition) of
 the person(s) providing the information, we produced different versions
 of the video.
 In each version of the video, the information was exactly the same, only
 the person (or persons) that featured in the video and explained everything
 was changed.
 In one version of the video, all the information is provided by an individual
 male farmer, while in a second version of the video, the information is
 given by a female farmer.
 In a third version of the video, the exact same information is given by
 a couple, each spouse taking turns in explaining things.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the farm household level, we find that providing information to farmers
 through short video messages increases their knowledge about modern inputs,
 improved technologies, and recommended practices.
 In addition, farmers who were shown the video are also more likely to adopt
 a range of inputs, technologies, and practices that were presented in the
 videos.
 We also find clear effects on production with maize yields 14 percent higher
 than in control households.
 However, these results do not translate into higher well-being.
 The IVR has no additional knowledge impact.
 The additional effect on technology adoption of IVR is also less significant:
 we only find a positive effect on the uptake of hybrid seed.
 Still, we do find that households that were allocated to the IVR treatment
 report yields that are 8 percent higher.
 The sms campaign has no additional impact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Within the household, we find greater nuance to these initial findings.
 First, the observed yield gains are observed on male- and jointly-managed
 plots: although we observe that providing information through the video
 messages increases women's involvement in decision making.
 However, the increase in participation in decision making does not translated
 into higher yields on women-managed plots.
 
\end_layout

