\begin_layout Section*
Research Questions and Hypotheses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, we investigate the effectiveness of delivering agricultural
 extension information to Ugandan smallholder farmers.
 We examine the relative importance of (i) the way the information is delivered,
 (ii) the gender composition of the messenger(s), and (iii) the gender compositi
on of the viewer(s) in encouraging the uptake and adoption of modern input
 use and improved crop management practices.
 Specific emphasis is placed on exploring both the effectiveness and inclusivity
 of this ICT-enabled approach to extension information delivery for several
 reasons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we contribute to the literature on how ICTs can improve crop management
 practices among smallholder farmers—a topic that has received considerable
 attention in recent years but has lacked sufficient evidence on which approache
s work and for whom 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1111/agec.12314"

\end_inset

.
 The role of ICTs in improving access to information on crop management—as
 compared to improving access to market and price information—is a particularly
 challenging area.
 Information of this kind is often non-excludable and non-rival in nature,
 requiring government intervention when it is under-supplied by the private
 sector.
 Government intervention typically takes the form of information campaigns,
 extension programs, and advisory services which have been met with mixed
 success 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Feder2010,doi:10.1080/13892240903309595,doi:10.1596/1813-9450-2129,doi:10.1080/13892249985300061"

\end_inset

.
 These ambiguous outcomes are often associated with specificities of the
 technology, practice, or principle being promoted; the agroecological and
 socioeconomic context in which it is being promoted; and other confounding
 factors that may be poorly understood or too costly to address in program
 design and implementation..
 As a result, ICT applications to extension such as sms reminders, purpose-built
 smartphone apps, portable tablets and projectors, and other hardware and
 software solutions have received considerable attention in recent years
 as a means of addressing some—if not all—of these issues.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several studies have reported positive impacts of ICTs applied to extension
 services.
 For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:hbs:wpaper:13-047"

\end_inset

 found that short message services (SMSs) pushed to farmers in Gujarat,
 India generated positive effects on crop choice and pesticide use decision
 and that the introduction of an interactive voice respose system signficantly
 increased cummin and cotton yields.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1080/00220388.2016.1146700"

\end_inset

 found that a multi-media mobile phone-based product linked to expert advisory
 services increased farmers' awareness and knowledge about specific solutions
 to their production constraints in Madhya Pradesh, India.
 Maredia et al., on the other hand, found that while mobile phone-based animated
 videos shown to farmers in Burkina Faso induced learning and understanding,
 it was no more effective in encouraging adoption.
 Similarly, Grameen Foundation had some success using smartphones in Uganda
 to provide agriculture-related information to farmers through community
 knowledge workers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1080/1369118X.2016.1200644"

\end_inset

.
 Also in Uganda, showning short videos to potato farmers increases their
 knowledge on seed selection, storage and handling 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1371/journal.pone.0169557"

\end_inset

.
 For recent reviews of this literature, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1146/annurev-resource-100913-012714"

\end_inset

.
 However, it remains to be seen how far these effects and be generalized,
 and questions about cost-effectiveness, scalability, and accountability
 often remain unaddressed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, we address the persistent issue of gender bias in the provision
 of agricultural extension services and the dissemination of information
 to smallholder farmers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doss200127,FLETSCHNER20111422,peterman2011understanding,QUISUMBING2010581"

\end_inset

.
 Often, extension agents are male, and their default strategy for disseminating
 information on crop management is to target the main (or most accessible)
 decision-maker in a household, who is assumed to be male.
 The assumption that extension messages targeting one household member will
 spread to other household members—including women and youth who often play
 a substantial role in agriculture—may be false 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RePEc:fpr:ifprid:1411"

\end_inset

.
 Men do not necessarily discuss production decisions or share information
 to women household members, especially if extension messages focus on men's
 priorities and crops 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "fletschner2011gender"

\end_inset

.
 Rather, evidence suggests that in certain contexts, gender homophily effects
 in whichmen learn more from other men and women learn more from other women,
 may dominate other intra-household information-sharing effects 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doss200127"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third, we explore this issue further by investigating the extent to which
 farms are managed at the household level in a cooperative manner, e.g., through
 joint decision-making between and among male and female co-heads of household.
 This expands on recent advances in the measurement of gendered dimensions
 of empowerment, including decison-making power, intra-household distribution
 of decision-making power and control over income and resources 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ALKIRE201371,MAHMUD2012610"

\end_inset

.
 We further examine if women's involvement in and benefits from maize farming
 can be increased by questioning cultural norms and influencing aspirations
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RePEc:smu:ecowpa:1705,riley"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally and more broadly, we contribute to long-standing research efforts
 to document and measure the adoption and impact of improved agricultural
 technologies and practices among smallholder farmers.
 There are many reasons for the observed low rates of adoption of improved
 technologies and practices among smallholder farmers, including lack of
 access to credit and insurance, poorly developed labour markets, and asymmetrie
s of information 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1086/451461,jack2013market"

\end_inset

.
 Our contribution is methodological in nature in recognition of two important
 points.
 First, too few studies apply sufficiently rigorous methods to address concerns
 about sample selection bias and causal identification in the study of technical
 change in developing-country agriculture 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "de2010recent"

\end_inset

.
 Second, too few studies on ICT-enabled extension are replicated in differing
 contexts and populations to increase both generalizable findings and nuanced
 insights on the impact pathways through which ICT operates on farmers'
 decision-making about technology adoption.
 Our study adds to this growing body of literature and adapts a somewhat
 similar design under investigation in Ethiopia 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "tanguydiggreen"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our experimental design (described in detail below) allows us to explore
 these research questions by comparing outcomes between groups of randomly
 assigned farmers that are given the opportunity to view versions of a video
 on improved maize management practices in different configurations.
 In addition to the video, a random group of farmers will also receive a
 phone number and instructions to call into the IVR system.
 A final ramdom subset of these farmers will also be targetted by 10 sms
 messages reminding them at specific times about important practices and
 the fact that they can always call the IRV.
 The experiment allows us to test the following three hypotheses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
H1: Improving the provision of information to smallholder farmers results
 in increases in awareness and knowledge about improved technologies and
 practices, increases in the adoption of these technologies and practices,
 improvements in on-farm productivity gains, and improvements in household
 welfare.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many reasons for the observed low rates of adoption of improved
 technologies and practices among smallholder farmers.
 These include a lack of access to credit, missing risk markets, and poorly
 developed labour markets 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1086/451461,jack2013market"

\end_inset

.
 We focus on the role of information inefficiencies and test low-cost interventi
ons designed to address various types of information gaps.
 Similar information interventions using ICT have been promising and include
 the Grameen Foundation's use of smart phones in Uganda to provide extension
 information through community knowledge workers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1080/1369118X.2016.1200644"

\end_inset

 and a mobile phone based technology that allowed farmers to call a hotline
 and ask questions to agricultural scientists and extension workers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RePEc:hbs:wpaper:13-047"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
H2: The effectiveness of information depends on who is targeted: jointly
 to male and female co-heads in a household or only the female co-head in
 the household as opposed to only to the male co-head.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This hypothesis addresses the intra-household asymmetries of information
 that can lead to constrained decision-making on the adoption of new technologie
s and practices, and sub-optimal intra-household allocations of productive
 resources.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kabunga2012heterogeneous"

\end_inset

 find that female farmers are less likely to adopt tissue-culture banana
 technology in Kenya, but would have an equal chance to adopt the technology
 were they able to acquire sufficient information about it.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1093/erae/jbv039"

\end_inset

 investigate the effect of gendered approaches to extension training among
 farmers in South Kivu, DR Congo, and find that joint male and female participat
ion leads to the highest adoption rates for several key technologies and
 practices.
 Mechanisms that explain these effects focus largely on changes in n relative
 bargaining power of the actors, gender-linked differences in access to
 complementary inputs, and overall intensity of exposure to information
 and training (see, e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Doss200127"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
H3: The effectiveness of information depends on who brings the information:
 jointly by male and female co-heads in a household or only the female co-head
 in the household as opposed to only the the male co-head.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this hypothesis we will test is whether bringing the messages as a couple
 or as a female leads to better outcomes than when the information is given
 by a man as would be the default case.
 This hypothesis is based on the assumption that social norms prevent women
 from playing a more prominent role in household agriculture.
 Gender stereotyping, where women are expected to tend to small gardens
 used to produce for home consumption and men are responsible for cash crops
 using inputs obtained from the market, may contribute to inefficient allocation
 of resources within the household as a single unit of production.
 Research on how information campaigns can be used to change beliefs, norms
 and perceptions has been ongoing in public health and has only recently
 started to trickle through to other disciplines.
 Encouraging results emerge with respect to the importance of role models
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RePEc:smu:ecowpa:1705,riley"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

